## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws on macOS â€” it still works on Windows and Linux, but Apple dropped DSA support from their crypto libraries.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy DSA signatures, you have two options:

### Option 1: Use a software-based DSA implementation (keep cross-platform)
If you must continue verifying existing DSA signatures on macOS, run the verification on Windows/Linux only, or use a third-party crypto library (e.g., Bouncy Castle) that provides a managed DSA implementation.

### Option 2: Migrate to a modern algorithm (recommended long-term)
Re-sign with a modern algorithm and verify using that instead:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 10) â€” breaks on macOS in .NET 11
using var dsa = DSA.Create();
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);

// After â€” use ECDSA or RSA
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

Recommended replacements: **ECDSA** (preferred), **RSA**, or **Ed25519**.

### Option 3: Runtime guard
If migration takes time, guard the call so macOS gets a clear error:

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA is not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");
```

Since your use case is verifying **legacy** signatures you can't re-sign, a managed crypto library like **BouncyCastle** (`Portable.BouncyCastle` NuGet package) is likely the most practical fix â€” it provides a pure-managed DSA that works on all platforms.
